                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 7.69,
                                "byte_start": 105472,
                                "byte_stop": 136296,
                                "text": "Justice Breyer has the announcement of the Court in case 08-1341 United States versus Marcus."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 7.69,
                        "stop": 183.458,
                        "byte_start": 136296,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15139,
                            "name": "Stephen G. Breyer",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/stephen_g_breyer",
                            "last_name": "Breyer",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2785,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 775890000,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Bill Clinton",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2785"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32682,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 49908,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/stephen_g_breyer_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 7777,
                            "identifier": "stephen_g_breyer"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 7.69,
                                "stop": 18.651,
                                "byte_start": 136296,
                                "byte_stop": 180078,
                                "text": "The jury convicted the respondent Glenn Marcus of sex trafficking crimes that took place between \u201cJanuary 1999 and October 2001\u201d."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 18.651,
                                "stop": 33.606,
                                "byte_start": 180078,
                                "byte_stop": 239950,
                                "text": "On appeal, for the first time on appeal, Marcus pointed out that the relevant statute that he was convicted under, had not become enactive, wasn\u0027t enacted into law into well in between this period of time in October 2000."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 33.606,
                                "stop": 45.652,
                                "byte_start": 239950,
                                "byte_stop": 288120,
                                "text": "He said the jury might have based its conviction on events that took place before the statute became law and that the Constitution consequently required a new trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 45.652,
                                "stop": 82.2,
                                "byte_start": 288120,
                                "byte_stop": 434301,
                                "text": "Now everyone agrees in this case that the Constitution would forbid the jury to convict Marcus solely on the basis of conduct that was not unlawful at that time because the statute hadn\u2019t passed and that a failure to give the jury an appropriate instruction that would\u0027ve made sure, they knew that, was a mistake, an error and for present purposes, we have to assume that the error was clear enough in this case that it might qualify as a \u201cplain error\u0022 which is the kind of error, Court of Appeals can take into account even if the defendant doesn\u0027t raise the matter of trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 82.2,
                                "stop": 104.846,
                                "byte_start": 434301,
                                "byte_stop": 524894,
                                "text": "But still they will take this into account as a \u201cplain error\u201d only if among other things, it affects the defendant substantial rights and here the government argued there\u0027s so little chance that the jury would really have in this case based its conviction solely on the basis of conduct before the statute was enacted, the court should just ignore this mistake."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 104.846,
                                "stop": 112.258,
                                "byte_start": 524894,
                                "byte_stop": 554569,
                                "text": "Now the Court of Appeals rejected the government\u2019s argument, but not because it thought the error, probably made a difference in the case."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 112.258,
                                "stop": 133.84,
                                "byte_start": 554569,
                                "byte_stop": 640878,
                                "text": "It didn\u0027t decide, whether the error did or did not make a difference in the case, rather it rejected the error because in its view and here I quote the standard that it put down, \u201ca retrial is necessary whenever there is any possibility, no matter how unlikely, that the jury could have convicted based exclusively on pre-enactment conduct.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 133.84,
                                "stop": 149.447,
                                "byte_start": 640878,
                                "byte_stop": 703363,
                                "text": "Now no other Circuit has followed that kind of rule and in this case, we hold that the Second Circuit standard is inconsistent with this Court\u0027s holding setting forth the requirements about when Courts can recognize and when they can\u0027t recognize a \u201cplain error\u201d."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 149.447,
                                "stop": 155.395,
                                "byte_start": 703363,
                                "byte_stop": 727082,
                                "text": "The requirements which stem from the rules require a greater likelihood."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 155.395,
                                "stop": 160.56,
                                "byte_start": 727082,
                                "byte_stop": 747771,
                                "text": "Then the Second Circuit said that the error really did make a difference."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 160.56,
                                "stop": 176.364,
                                "byte_start": 747771,
                                "byte_stop": 810987,
                                "text": "The words, any possibility, no matter how unlikely, suggested it needn\u0027t have made any difference at all but the law requires it to have made a difference, so we remand the case so that it considered, it can reconsider it applying the correct \u201cplain error\u201d standard."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 176.364,
                                "stop": 178.989,
                                "byte_start": 810987,
                                "byte_stop": 821436,
                                "text": "Justice Stevens has filed a dissenting opinion."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 178.989,
                                "stop": 183.458,
                                "byte_start": 821436,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Sotomayor took no part in the consideration or decision of the case."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
